{
    "name": "Giant Belostomatid",
    "type": "monster",
    "sections": [
        {
            "name": "Ecology",
            "type": "section",
            "html": "<b>Environment</b> temperate lakes, rivers, or swamps<br/><b>Organization</b> solitary<br/><b>Treasure</b> incidental"
        },
        {
            "name": "Special Abilities",
            "type": "section",
            "html": "<b>Digestive Enzyme (Ex)</b> A giant belostomatid injects a corrosive enzyme that paralyzes its prey. A creature bitten by this insect must succeed at a DC 15 Fortitude save or be paralyzed for 1d4 rounds. Each round, the creature can attempt a new save; on a failure it is still paralyzed and takes 1d2 points of Constitution damage. The save DC is Constitution-based."
        },
        {
            "name": "Description",
            "type": "section",
            "html": "The giant belostomatid is an ambush predator that lurks in shallow water and hides amid floating snags and debris. Smaller versions of these insects are known colloquially as \u201ctoebiters,\u201d yet this version of the creature is the size of a horse and can sever the leg of a human in one bite."
        }
    ],
    "html": "<i>Six powerful legs, each ending in a hooked claw, jut from the shield-like body of this horse-sized insect.</i>",
